div.p:
Occurrence of veterinary pharmaceuticals in the environment is an emerging scientific issue (Brown et al.

 2006

; Kolpin et al.

 2002

). The active medical substances discharged with manure are washed off from agricultural soil and move into aquatic systems during precipitation. Various kinds of medicines released into the environment bring about adverse effects on aquatic and terrestrial organisms as well as on human beings, such as malfunctions in physiological systems and the induction of specific diseases (Sarmah et al.

 2006

). Moreover, pharmaceutical compounds are refractory to biodegradation in the environment, with half-life time ranging from months to years (Boxall

 2008

). The accumulation of manufactured antibiotics in environment is a global issue that would require regulations to manage.

Sulfonamide veterinary antibiotics are widely used in commercial animal feeding in order to prevent infectious diseases and to promote animal growth (Aust et al.

 2008

). They are regarded as emerging pollutants introduced to the environment predominantly in developed countries (Korea Food and Drug Administration

 2006

; Veterinary Medicines Directorate

 2005

). For example, extensive monitoring studies performed in German agricultural areas showed that a large number of soils and groundwater was contaminated by sulfonamides residues (Hirsch et al.

 1999

; Höper et al.

 2002

). In the agricultural lands fertilised with manure, the concentration of sulfadimidine was detected up to 11 μg/kg (Höper et al.

 2002

). Maximum concentrations of the sulfonamides in groundwater below the German crop land ranged from 0.16 μg/L (sulfadimidine) to 0.47 μg/L (sulfamethoxazole) (Hirsch et al.

 1999

). In Korea, many sulfonamides such as sulfadimethoxine and sulfamethoxazole have been frequently detected in surface waters ranged to 26.9 ng/L (Park

 2005

; Choi et al.

 2008

). The wide range in concentrations indicates broad variability in input and transport processes of individual sulfonamide antibiotics within the vadose zone.

Several approaches have been used to estimate the interaction between sulfonamide antibiotics and soil (Fan et al.

 2011

; Unold et al.

 2009

; Wehrhan et al.

 2007

). Batch sorption experiments have been conducted to evaluate sorption coefficients concerning mobility of the pharmaceuticals. Holten-Lützhøft et al. (

 2000

) and Tolls (

 2001

) suggested possible mechanisms for the sorption of sulfonamides include cation exchange, cation bridging, surface complexes, hydrophobic partitioning and electrostatic interactions. Since sulfonamide antibiotics can be ionised in water, many sorption studies have focused on relation between ionisation and sorption. Kahle and Stamm (

 2007

) investigated the sorption of sulfathiazole on soil and natural organic sorbents. They concluded that the sorption was significantly higher in case of presence of organic sorbents. Thiele-Bruhn and Aust (

 2004

) studied the effects of pig manure on the sorption of five sulfonamides in soil. They showed that sorption of the sulfonamides was decreased in a mixture of soil and manure. Their results also suggested that pH changes caused by manure amendment increased sorption, due to change of ionisation status of sorbents.

Although the approaches can properly define transport behaviour of pharmaceuticals under restricted conditions, it is difficult to apply results from the laboratory-scale studies to in situ, due to soil heterogeneity, macropore flow and varying climatic condition (Burkhardt and Stamm

 2007

). A few studies on transport of the pharmaceuticals have been performed in situ or in closed to field conditions (Burkhardt and Stamm

 2007

). Studies by Burkhardt et al. (

 2005

) and Burkhardt and Stamm (

 2007

) observed transport of a sulfadimidine, sulfadiazine and sulfathiazole spread on undisturbed loamy grassland soil. The studies showed preferential flow and surface runoff were important pathways for the fate of sulfonamides. A study by Burkhardt et al. (

 2005

) showed that surface runoff and leaching were two important transport pathways of SDZ. Kim et al. (

 2010

) investigated loss of several pharmaceuticals (e.g. tetracycline and sulfathiazole) by precipitation. The highest concentration of each pharmaceutical in the top soil was observed at different locations. The results indicated that their mobility on soil surface are dependent on physico-chemical properties of the applied compounds. Furthermore, sulfathiazole can penetrate into deeper subsurface, while tetracycline and tylosin remain in the upper soil layer. However, a critical limitation of the previous studies is the missing quantitative approach describing transport of the antibiotics in surface and subsurface using numerical modelling techniques.

The Haean catchment is located in North-eastern part of Gangwon Province in South Korea. Dryland farming is dominant in the mountainous area of the catchment, while rice cultivation is mostly practised in the flat agricultural areas. The average precipitation is about 1500 mm/year, and 50–60 % of total annual precipitation is concentrated in summer monsoon from June to July. However, frequency and amount of rainfall increased from late July to mid-August, because withdrawal time for summer monsoon has tended to be late in the recent decade (Ha et al.

 2005

).

In order to estimate runoff generation, we installed a runoff sampler designed by Bonilla et al. (

 2006

). The sampler included a runoff collector connected with a PVC pipe to a multislot divisor suggested by Pinson et al. (

 2003

). For the runoff collector, we used the configuration for small fields suggested by Bonilla et al. (

 2006

). This configuration consisted of three 20-L buckets, one with a 12-slot divisor and the others with 24-slot divisors. The runoff collector was placed at a point where all runoff from the plots was expected. The flow dividers were installed in buried boxes suggested by Bonilla et al. (

 2006

). During rainfall periods, we estimated a volume of runoff for each bucket using a pressure sensor equipped in each bucket. During runoff generation, we took runoff samples in front of the first multislot divisor. The volume of runoff from each plot was estimated by the following equation (Bonilla et al.

 2006

).

To determine hydraulic and solute transport parameters using inverse modelling, HydroGeoSphere was coupled with a parameter optimisation tool, Parallel PEST (version 12.1.0, Doherty

 2005

). Initial values of the Van Genuchten parameters were obtained using Rosetta Lite (version 1.1), implementing hierarchical pedotransfer functions for estimating water retention characteristics (Schaap et al.

 2001

).

Values of longitudinal dispersivities were estimated between 0.01 and 0.5 m in accordance with findings of previous study (Gelhar et al.

 1992

). According to previous findings by Marsily (

 1986

), initial values of transversal and vertical transversal dispersivity were set to 0.001 m and afterwards optimised in a range from 0.0001 to 0.01 m. Since sulfonamide antibiotics were absorbable onto soil and low volatile, the volatilization process was ignored. Adsorption coefficients (

 K


 d

) of the sulfonamides and bromide estimated from our batch sorption experiment were used for retardation factor.

The diffusion coefficient of sulfonamides was calculated using Stokes-Einstein equation based on molecular weight. Degradation rate of the sulfonamide antibiotics in soil and soil water system is low under both aerobic and anaerobic conditions (Kunkel and Radke

 2008

; Radke et al.

 2009

). For parameter estimation, we used an initial degradation rate (0.04 day

 −1

) suggested by previous study (Radke et al.

 2009

).

To evaluate the model, the coefficient of determination (

 R


 2

) and the Nash-Sutcliffe efficiency (NSE) was estimated (Nash and Sutcliffe

 1970

). The coefficient of determination is between 0 and 1.0. The NSE is a normalised measure which compares the mean square error generated by a hydrological simulation with the variance of the target output sequence. The range of NSE lies between −∞ and 1.0. NSE value = 1.0 indicates perfect model performance, and an NSE value <0 indicates that the observed mean is a better predictor than the model.

Typical monsoon rains were observed during the experiment (Fig.

 2

). Strong precipitation from 24 June to 10 July generated both surface runoff and subsurface flow in soil. From 24 June, several strong rain events were observed up to 126 mm/day, and the hourly intensity of rainfall varied from 0 to 23 mm/h. Runoff generation correlated with the rain intensity during the entire experiment period. Slope of the experiment fields also affected runoff. Compared with field B, runoff generation from field A was more frequent. The amount of runoff generation was relatively high (field A, 0–84.18 L/h; field B, 0–70.42 L/h). Even low precipitation events generated surface runoff on both fields during the rainy season, since the water content of the subsurface region was higher than during dry season (23 May–23 June). From 2 to 23 June, no runoff was generated even though two rain events occurred.

On hillside region, runoff generation is dependent on the shape of the surface, soil texture and slope (Chaplot and Le Bissonnais

 2003

; Assouline and Ben-Hur

 2006

). A study performed in this region showed that runoff generation in ridge-furrow system during the monsoon season can be affected by slope (Arnhold et al.

 2013

). Another study revealed that difference of runoff in ridge-furrow system was caused by varying saturated hydraulic conductivities of top soils (Ruidisch et al.

 2013

). As shown in Table

 1

, the texture of the soils of both agricultural field sites was sandy loam, and both were managed by the characteristic ridge-furrow system on the surface. When the soil is characterised by similar soil texture and same ridge-furrow system, amount of runoff generation is not different (Arnhold et al.

 2013

). Therefore, the difference of runoff generation was associated with the slope of the experiment fields.

Concentration of the target antibiotics and conservative tracer (Br

 −

) in runoff varied between two fields, due to runoff generation and slope of the observed fields. As the sulfonamide antibiotics and bromide were applied in the upper 2 cm of the top soil, they were easily washed out by the first rain event on 31 May. After starting intensive precipitation on 23 June, very low concentrations of bromide were detected. Owing to very low adsorption on soil material, the conservative tracer was rapidly infiltrated into deeper layers and runoff at beginning of the rainy season.

Concentrations of the antibiotics were fluctuated during the heavy rain event. The rain intensity varied, and soil loss caused by runoff corresponded to the rain intensity in the agricultural lands. Total suspended particle (TSS) in the runoff samples were from 67 to 3750 mg/L and was dependent on rain intensity. The chosen antibiotics adsorbed onto soil particle were transported by runoff. The above result implies that the sulfonamide movement by runoff is a typical particle-facilitated transport. For the sulfonamide antibiotics, soil-suspended particles and humic substance provides binding sites where additional partitioning can occur (Wegst-Uhrich et al.

 2014

). The sulfonamides tend to adsorb to surface of soil particle and absorb into organic substance in surface of the particle (Schwarz et al.

 2012

). The runoff contained soil particles which can facilitate transport of sorbing contaminants like the sulfonamides. When the runoff was generated, soil particle-sulfonamide complexes were formed. Therefore, concentration of the antibiotics was associated with the soil particles. In this regard, finer particles are of more concern than larger particles, because they have relatively higher surface area (Sansalone et al.

 1998

; Herngren et al.

 2006

).

